Project Introduction: Car Make and Model Recognition System¶

1. Data Requirements Documentation¶

Purpose of the Documentation¶

This documentation serves as a comprehensive guide for managing and utilizing data in the development of a car make and model recognition system. It outlines the types of data needed, quality standards, and ethical considerations, ensuring that the project's goals are met effectively and responsibly.

Data Elements¶

Each data element is crucial for a thorough understanding of the automotive industry and for conducting detailed analyses. Here's a breakdown of these elements:

Identify Data Types¶

  1. Numerical Data

    • Vehicle Year:
      • Description: Year of manufacture of the vehicles.
      • Units: Year (e.g., 2012, 2020)
      • Importance: Critical for identifying the model year of the car.
      • Source: Automotive databases and car listings or websited like kaggle.
      • Quality standards: Years from the last 10 years and to use realistc years.
      • Ethical Considerations: All of the data is collected legaly and can be used in academic work.
      • Project Relevance: Essential for distinguishing between different generations of the same car model.

  2. Categorical Data

    • Car Make and Model:
      • Description: The brand and specific model of the vehicle.
      • Categories: Various car brands and models (e.g., BMW M3, Tesla Model S).
      • Importance: Fundamental for the classification task of the project.
      • Source: Automotive databases, manufacturer websites and websites like kaggle.
      • Quality Standards: High accuracy in labeling the images and using real models.
      • Ethical Considerations: The data accured is open for the public and not classified.
      • Project Relevance: Core to the system’s capability to recognize and differentiate between various cars.

  3. Image Data

    • Car Images:
      • Description: Photographs of cars from various angles.
      • Resolution: Resolutions atleast 400x400 or higher.
      • Range: Images covering a wide variety of car brands.
      • Importance: Vital for training the image recognition model.
      • Source: Online car databases, user-submitted images and websited like kaggle.
      • Quality Standards: Images that have a clear view of the car and images that are not blurry.
      • Ethical Considerations: Usage of images compliant with copyright laws.
      • Project Relevance: The primary data type used for training and testing the model.

2. Data Collection Process¶

Overview¶

The data for this project is from Stanford Car Dataset.

Collection Methodology¶

  • Download from webiste:
    • The dataset was downloaded from kaggle.
  • Data Storage:
    • Data was stored in an organized manner, with images categorized by make and model.
    • Metadata about each car (like make and year) was stored in corresponding CSV files.

Compliance and Security¶

  • Data Protection: Ensured all collected data complies with relevant data privacy and protection laws.
  • Usage Rights: Ensured all images and data used are either publicly available or used with permission.

I will start by checking the number of images contained in each directory, which represents a different car model. Seing what there average is, how many images there are and how many vehicle classes there are.

The count_images function is designed to traverse a specified directory and perform two primary tasks:

  • Image Counting: It counts the number of image files within each subdirectory of the provided directory.
  • Class Counting: It determines the number of unique classes, which are represented by the subdirectories.
In [ ]:
def count_images(directory):
    """Count the number of images in each subdirectory and the total number of unique classes."""
    total_images = 0
    subdirectories = os.listdir(directory)
    for subdir in subdirectories:
        subdir_path = os.path.join(directory, subdir)
        num_images = len([file for file in os.listdir(subdir_path) if os.path.isfile(os.path.join(subdir_path, file))])
        total_images += num_images
        print(f"{subdir}: {num_images} images")
    return subdirectories, total_images

Lets break down the results.¶

Both the training and testing sets feature 196 unique vehicle classes, offering a diverse representation of car models. The dataset contains a total of 16,185 images, with 8,144 in the training set and 8,041 in the testing set and the average number of images per car class for both is approximately 41. While this numbers gives a general idea, the actual number of images per class changes. For example, the Chrysler 300 SRT-8 2010 class has the highest number of images at 49, while the Hyundai Accent Sedan 2012 has the lowest with only 24 images.

The class 'Hyundai Accent Sedan 2012' has only 24 images which imposes a risk that the model underperforms when accurately recognizing the class and this shows in the recall(0.83) and f1-score(0.87) accuracy of this class, thats why I will try to artificially augment the dataset. The primary goal is to bolster the Hyundai Accent Sedan 2012 class, bringing its image count closer to the average by implementing a series of image transformations, such as rotations, flips, and color adjustments, on the existing images.

In [ ]:
def augment_images(image_folder, class_name, target_count):
    transform = transforms.Compose([
        transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
        transforms.RandomRotation(15),
        transforms.ColorJitter(brightness=0.5, contrast=0.5, saturation=0.5),
    ])

    class_path = os.path.join(image_folder, class_name)
    images = [os.path.join(class_path, img) for img in os.listdir(class_path)]
    num_images = len(images)

    while num_images < target_count:
        img_path = random.choice(images)
        img = Image.open(img_path)
        new_img = transform(img)

        new_img_path = os.path.join(class_path, f"aug_{num_images}.jpg")
        new_img.save(new_img_path)

        num_images += 1

augment_images('./car_data/train','Hyundai Accent Sedan 2012', 20)

The augmentation is succesfull because the accuracy went up. The recall is now 0.92 and the f1-score is 0.92.

This code is designed to process a directory structure containing images of cars, where each subdirectory is named in a 'Year Make Model' format, indicating the year, make, and model of the car. It collects information about the number of images available for each car model and organizes this data into a structured format using a pandas DataFrame. Let's break down the code.

In [ ]:
#each folder name is in the 'Year Make Model' format
def extract_info_from_folder(folder_name):
    parts = folder_name.split()
    year = parts[-1]  # The last part is the year
    make = parts[0]   # The first part is the make
    model = ' '.join(parts[1:-1])  # The middle part(s) is/are the model
    return year, make, model

# Path to the dataset directories
train_dir = './car_data/train'
test_dir = './car_data/test'

# Initialize a list to hold the data
data = []

# Function to process a directory and append data
def process_directory(directory):
    for folder_name in os.listdir(directory):
        year, make, model = extract_info_from_folder(folder_name)
        image_count = len([file for file in os.listdir(os.path.join(directory, folder_name)) if os.path.isfile(os.path.join(directory, folder_name, file))])
        data.append({'Year': year, 'Make': make, 'Model': model, 'ImageCount': image_count})

# Process both training and testing directories
process_directory(train_dir)
process_directory(test_dir)

# Convert the list to a pandas DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame(data)

image_counts = df.groupby(['Make', 'Model', 'Year'])['ImageCount'].sum().reset_index()

Now I am going to check if there is a pattern or trend of the number of images based on the year and model of the vehicles.

Since the dataset contains around 16000 images there might be some which are blurry and this might lower the accuracy of the machine learning model. The following code will take care of that. Using cv2 which is a open-source computer vision and machine learning software library used for image processing, I will try to find blurry images and move them to a seperate folder.

In [ ]:
# Set the threshold for blur detection
blur_threshold = 100

def is_blurry(image_path, threshold=blur_threshold):
    image = cv2.imread(str(image_path))
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    laplacian = cv2.Laplacian(gray, cv2.CV_64F)
    laplacian_variance = laplacian.var()
    return laplacian_variance < threshold

def move_blurry_images(directory_path, destination_base_folder="blurry", sample_limit=10):
    moved_count = 0
    sample_images = []
    car_names = []

    # Create base blurry folder
    blurry_base_folder_path = Path(destination_base_folder)
    blurry_base_folder_path.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

    for brand_folder in directory_path.iterdir():
        if brand_folder.is_dir():
            # Create brand specific folder inside blurry base folder
            blurry_folder_path = blurry_base_folder_path / directory_path.name / brand_folder.name
            blurry_folder_path.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

            for image_path in brand_folder.glob("*.[jJ][pP][gG]"):
                if is_blurry(image_path):
                    move(str(image_path), str(blurry_folder_path / image_path.name))
                    moved_count += 1

                    if len(sample_images) < sample_limit:
                        sample_images.append(str(blurry_folder_path / image_path.name))
                        car_names.append(brand_folder.stem)

    print(f"Total moved from {directory_path.name}: {moved_count}")
    return sample_images, car_names

# path to image datasets
train_path = Path('./car_data/train')
test_path = Path('./car_data/test')

# Move blurry images and get sample image paths for both train and test datasets
train_samples, train_car_names = move_blurry_images(train_path)
test_samples, test_car_names = move_blurry_images(test_path)

# Combine samples and car names from both train and test datasets
all_samples = train_samples + test_samples
all_car_names = train_car_names + test_car_names

# Adjust the subplot size based on the number of images
num_samples = len(all_samples)
cols = 5
rows = num_samples // cols + (num_samples % cols > 0)

# Display sample blurry images from both train and test datasets

    plt.subplot(rows, cols, i + 1)

    plt.axis('off')

Preprocessing¶

In this step, I will prepare the images for the machine learning algorithm. This includes several transformation processes designed to both standardize the input data and augment the training dataset to improve generalization of the model.

Train Transformations¶

Resize:

  • transforms.Resize((400, 400)): This transformation resizes each image to a fixed size of 400x400 pixels. This uniformity is crucial because neural networks typically require inputs of the same dimensions.

Random Horizontal Flip:

  • transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(): This applies a random horizontal flip to the images. With a default probability of 50%, it mirrors the image along the vertical axis. This randomization increases the diversity of the training data, helping to prevent overfitting and improve the model's generalization.

Random Rotation:

  • transforms.RandomRotation(15): This rotates the image by a random angle within ±15 degrees. This slight rotation adds variety to the training dataset, further aiding the model's ability to generalize.

ToTensor:

  • transforms.ToTensor(): Converts the image to a PyTorch tensor, changing the image from a range of 0-255 to 0-1 (normalizing pixel values).

Normalize:

  • transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406], [0.229, 0.224, 0.225]): This standardizes the pixel values across the dataset. The first list of numbers is the mean for each channel (RGB), and the second list is the standard deviation. This normalization helps in stabilizing the learning process.

ColorJitter:

  • transforms.ColorJitter(brightness=0.2, contrast=0.2, saturation=0.2, hue=0.1): This transformation randomly changes the brightness, contrast, saturation, and hue of the image. The parameters (0.2 for brightness, contrast, saturation, and 0.1 for hue) specify how much each attribute can vary. Adjusting these image attributes can make the model more robust to lighting changes and color variations in different environments.

RandomCrop:

  • transforms.RandomCrop(350): This transformation randomly crops the image to a size of 350x350 pixels. Cropping is done after resizing the image to 400x400 pixels, which means the crop will take a portion from the original image, adding variability to the position of the objects in the image. This can help the model learn to recognize objects regardless of their position within the image frame.
In [ ]:
train_transforms = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize((400, 400)),
    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
    transforms.RandomRotation(15),
    transforms.ColorJitter(brightness=0.2, contrast=0.2, saturation=0.2, hue=0.1),
    transforms.RandomCrop(350),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406], [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
])

Resizing:¶

All images are resized to a consistent dimension of 400x400 pixels. This standardization is crucial for neural network models to process batches of images efficiently.

Test Transformations¶

For the test dataset, the transformations are simpler, as we do not need the randomization used in training:

Resize:

  • The same resizing is applied to ensure the test images match the input size expected by the model. ToTensor and Normalize:

The same conversion to a tensor and normalization are applied for consistency with the training data.

In [ ]:
test_transforms = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize((400, 400)),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    transforms.Normalize([0.485, 0.456, 0.406], [0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
])

Hyperparameters¶

Now I will use Optuna, a hyperparameter optimization framework that intelligently navigates through vast parameter. The code was already executed and the best hyperparameter results were applid in the function because it takes a long time to run it(31 hours). These are the parameters set to the best value based on the Optuna results

  • lr (learning rate) is set to approximately 0.051. The learning rate is one of the most important hyperparameters in training neural networks. It controls the size of the steps the optimizer takes while adjusting the weights in the network.

  • momentum is a hyperparameter that helps accelerate the optimizer in the relevant direction and dampens oscillations. It's set to approximately 0.547.

  • step_size is set to 8. This value is assosiated with the learning rate scheduler ('StepLR'). The scheduler changes the learning rate according to a pre-defined schedule, which is critical in avoiding local minima and improving convergence.

  • gamma - In the context of the StepLR scheduler, gamma is the factor by which the learning rate will be multiplied after every step_size epochs. The best value is 0.2298444814148019.

The code here is used to optimize the model's performance by fine-tuning key hyperparameters, such as learning rate and momentum, through Optuna. This is achieved by iteratively training the model and evaluating its performance across different hyperparameter combinations, allowing for the identification and application of the most effective settings for the given dataset and task.

In [ ]:
def objective(trial):
    # range of values for the hyperparameters
    lr = trial.suggest_float("lr", 1e-5, 1e-1, log=True)
    momentum = trial.suggest_float("momentum", 0.4, 0.9)
    step_size = trial.suggest_int("step_size", 1, 10)
    gamma = trial.suggest_float("gamma", 0.1, 0.9)

    # Load a pre-trained ResNet-34 model and modify it for our dataset
    model = models.resnet34(pretrained=True)
    num_ftrs = model.fc.in_features
    model.fc = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, len(train_dataset.classes))
    model = model.to(device)

    criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
    optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=lr, momentum=momentum)
    scheduler = optim.lr_scheduler.StepLR(optimizer, step_size=step_size, gamma=gamma)

    return train_model(model, criterion, optimizer, scheduler, trial)

# Function to train the model
def train_model(model, criterion, optimizer, scheduler, trial, num_epochs=10):
    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()
        running_loss = 0.0
        running_corrects = 0

        for inputs, labels in train_loader:
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)

            optimizer.zero_grad()

            with torch.set_grad_enabled(True):
                outputs = model(inputs)
                loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
                _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)
                loss.backward()
                optimizer.step()

            running_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
            running_corrects += torch.sum(preds == labels.data)

        scheduler.step()

        epoch_loss = running_loss / len(train_loader.dataset)
        epoch_acc = running_corrects.double() / len(train_loader.dataset)

        trial.report(epoch_acc, epoch)

        if trial.should_prune():
            raise optuna.exceptions.TrialPruned()

    return epoch_acc

study = optuna.create_study(direction="maximize")
study.optimize(objective, n_trials=20)

print("Best hyperparameters: ", study.best_trial.params)

Now, I will apply the optimized parameters to the model using nn.CrossEntropyLoss() and optim.SGD.

  • nn.CrossEntropyLoss() is ideal for our multi-class classification problem as it efficiently combines log softmax and negative log likelihood loss, ensuring accurate probability distribution predictions. The chosen optim.SGD optimizer, with a learning rate of 0.05116282512153675 and momentum of 0.5470364990595213, as determined by Optuna, optimally updates the model's weights, while the StepLR scheduler adjusts the learning rate to enhance convergence as training progresses."

Evaluation¶

After setting up the model, we need to evaluate its performance. This involves running the model on the test dataset and measuring its accuracy and other metrics.

Training Function:

  • The train_model function trains the model over a specified number of epochs. During each epoch, it iterates over the training data, computes the loss, and updates the model's weights. It also prints the loss and accuracy for each epoch, which helps us monitor the training process.
In [ ]:
def train_model(model, criterion, optimizer, scheduler, num_epochs=10):
    train_losses = []
    train_accuracies = []

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()
        running_loss = 0.0
        running_corrects = 0

        for inputs, labels in train_loader:
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            optimizer.zero_grad()

            outputs = model(inputs)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()

            running_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
            running_corrects += torch.sum(preds == labels.data).item()  

        scheduler.step()
        epoch_loss = running_loss / len(train_loader.dataset)
        epoch_acc = running_corrects / len(train_loader.dataset)  

        train_losses.append(epoch_loss)
        train_accuracies.append(epoch_acc)  

        print('Epoch {}/{} - Loss: {:.4f} - Acc: {:.4f}'.format(
            epoch, num_epochs - 1, epoch_loss, epoch_acc))

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.plot(train_losses, label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(train_accuracies, label='Training Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss/Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training Performance')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    return model

Evaluation Function:

  • The evaluate_model function assesses the model's performance on the test data. It calculates the loss and accuracy and also provides a classification report, which includes metrics like precision, recall, and F1-score. It returns the accuracy score, which is a key metric to understand how well the model performs on unseen data.
In [ ]:
def evaluate_model(model, test_loader, criterion, device, test_dataset):
    model.eval()
    all_preds = []
    all_labels = []
    running_loss = 0.0
    running_corrects = 0

    with torch.no_grad():
        for inputs, labels in test_loader:
            inputs = inputs.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)

            outputs = model(inputs)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            _, preds = torch.max(outputs, 1)

            running_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
            running_corrects += torch.sum(preds == labels.data)

            all_preds.extend(preds.cpu().numpy())
            all_labels.extend(labels.cpu().numpy())

    epoch_loss = running_loss / len(test_loader.dataset)
    epoch_acc = running_corrects.double() / len(test_loader.dataset)

    print('Test Loss: {:.4f} Acc: {:.4f}'.format(epoch_loss, epoch_acc))
    print(classification_report(all_labels, all_preds, target_names=test_dataset.classes))

    return accuracy_score(all_labels, all_preds)

Model Training and Saving:

  • We train the model using the train_model function and save the trained model's state for future use. The evaluation of the model is done using the evaluate_model function to understand its performance on the test data.

The results of the project show a successful training process of a machine learning model for image classification with the final epoch (epoch 9/9) achieving a training loss of 0.0524 and an accuracy of 98.90%. This shows that the model has learned effectively from the training data, being able to predict the correct labels with high accuracy while minimizing the error (loss).

Upon evaluating the model on a test set, it achieved a test loss of 0.3386 and an accuracy of 91.15%. The accuracy remains high, but there is a noticeable increase in loss when comparing training and test results. This indicates that the model is slightly overfitting to the training data, although the high test accuracy indicates that the model is still generalizing well to unseen data.
